05112nam a22006735i 9780271022680DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710226807 a10.1515/97802710226802doi  a(DE-B1597)584433  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHD9005b.A69 2004 7aSOC0260202bisacsh04a338.1/09731 aAllen, Patricia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTogether at the Table :bSustainability and Sustenance in the American Agrifood System /cPatricia Allen. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRural Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcronyms -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Sustainability and Sustenance in the Agrifood System -- t2. Perspectives of Alternative Agrifood Movements: Issues and Concepts -- t3. Landscapes of Alternative Agrifood Movements: Institutional Integration and Construction -- t4. Discourses, Epistemologies, and Practices of Sustainability and Sustenance -- t5. Reflections on Ideologies Embedded in Alternative Agrifood Movements -- t6. Participation and Power in Alternative Agrifood Movements and Institutions -- t7. Politics of Complacency? Rethinking Food-System Localization -- t8. The Politics of Sustainability and Sustenance -- t9. Working Toward Sustainability and Sustenance -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEverywhere you look people are more aware of what they eat and where their food comes from. In a cafeteria in Los Angeles, children make their lunchtime food choices at fresh-fruit and salad bars stocked with local foods. In a community garden in New York, low-income residents are producing organically grown fruits and vegetables for their own use and to sell at market. In Madison, Wisconsin, shoppers select their food from a bounty of choices at a vibrant farmers' market. Together at the Table is about people throughout the United States who are building successful alternatives to the contemporary agrifood system and their prospects for the future. At the heart of these efforts are the movements for sustainable agriculture and community food security. Both movements seek to reconstruct the agrifood system-the food production chain, from the growing of crops to food production and distribution-to become more ecologically sound, economically viable, and socially just. Allen describes the ways in which people working in these movements view the world and how they see their place in challenging and reshaping the agrifood system. She also shows how ideas and practices of sustainable agriculture and community food security have already woven their way into the dominant agrifood institutions. Allen explores the possibilities this process may hold for improving social and environmental justice in the American agrifood system.Together at the Table is an important reminder that much work still remains to be done. Now that the ideas and priorities of alternative food movements have taken hold, it is time for the next-even more challenging-step. Alternative agrifood movements must acknowledge and address the deeper structural and cultural patterns that constrain the long-term resolution of social and environmental problems in the agrifood system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAgricultural industriesxEnvironmental aspectszUnited States. 0aFood industry and tradezUnited States. 0aNatural foods industryzUnited States. 0aSustainable agriculturexEconomic aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eB